{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_01LUEKa8Gi9pTsuqDtJKSiCB","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Wiki Page Template\n2\t\n3\tUse this template when creating new wiki pages. Copy the structure,\n4\tfill in the bracketed fields.\n5\t\n6\t---\n7\t\n8\t## Template\n9\t\n10\t```markdown\n11\t# <Page Title>\n12\t\n13\t<One-sentence summary of what this page covers.>\n14\t\n15\t## Key Points\n16\t\n17\t- <Bullet point 1: a concrete fact, concept, or takeaway>\n18\t- <Bullet point 2>\n19\t- <Bullet point 3>\n20\t- <Additional bullets as needed, max 10>\n21\t\n22\t## Related\n23\t\n24\t- [<Related Page Title>](<related-slug>.md) — <one-line reason for connection>\n25\t- [<Another Related Page>](<slug>.md) — <connection reason>\n26\t\n27\t## Sources\n28\t\n29\t- <path/to/source/file or URL where this came from>\n30\t- Ingested: <YYYY-MM-DD>\n31\t```\n32\t\n33\t---\n34\t\n35\t## Good Example\n36\t\n37\t```markdown\n38\t# Retrieval Augmented Generation\n39\t\n40\tTechnique that grounds LLM responses in retrieved documents rather than\n41\trelying solely on training data.\n42\t\n43\t## Key Points\n44\t\n45\t- Combines a retriever (vector search) with a generator (LLM)\n46\t- Reduces hallucination by providing source documents as context\n47\t- Trade-off: retrieval quality limits generation quality\n48\t- Common stack: embeddings → vector DB → reranker → LLM prompt\n49\t- Works best when source corpus is well-chunked and up-to-date\n50\t\n51\t## Related\n52\t\n53\t- [Vector Databases](vector-databases.md) — the retrieval layer in RAG pipelines\n54\t- [Agent Eval Harness](agent-eval-harness.md) — uses embedding similarity for judge calibration\n55\t\n56\t## Sources\n57\t\n58\t- ~/second-brain/sources/what-is-rag.md\n59\t- Ingested: 2026-06-10\n60\t```\n61\t\n62\t---\n63\t\n64\t## Bad Example\n65\t\n66\t```markdown\n67\t# RAG\n68\t\n69\tRetrieval Augmented Generation (RAG) is a technique in artificial intelligence\n70\tthat combines information retrieval with text generation. It was first proposed\n71\tby Lewis et al. in 2020. The basic idea is that instead of relying solely on\n72\twhat a language model learned during training, you can augment it with relevant\n73\tdocuments retrieved at inference time.\n74\t\n75\tThis approach has several advantages. First, it reduces hallucination because\n76\tthe model can reference actual documents. Second, it allows the model to access\n77\tup-to-date information that wasn't in its training data. Third, it provides\n78\ttransparency because you can trace responses back to source documents.\n79\t\n80\tThere are several implementations of RAG available today...\n81\t```\n82\t\n83\t**Why it's bad:**\n84\t- Reads like a Wikipedia article, not a wiki node\n85\t- No bullet summaries (walls of prose)\n86\t- No Related section (isolated page, no connections)\n87\t- No Sources section (where did this come from?)\n88\t- Title is an acronym without expansion\n89\t- Contains filler (\"There are several...\" \"This approach has...\")\n90\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"26577a53-3272-4cd4-9d88-de04f8cb372b","uuid":"b7061017-330b-49db-9fe0-3eed302befb8","timestamp":"2026-07-09T15:57:50.452Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/private/var/folders/kd/9pjy5r0x63g010533l28y0cc0000gn/T/agent-eval/2026-07-09-sonnet-v2/cases/ingest-raw-text/.claude/skills/second-brain-wiki/references/wiki-page-template.md","content":"# Wiki Page Template\n\nUse this template when creating new wiki pages. Copy the structure,\nfill in the bracketed fields.\n\n---\n\n## Template\n\n```markdown\n# <Page Title>\n\n<One-sentence summary of what this page covers.>\n\n## Key Points\n\n- <Bullet point 1: a concrete fact, concept, or takeaway>\n- <Bullet point 2>\n- <Bullet point 3>\n- <Additional bullets as needed, max 10>\n\n## Related\n\n- [<Related Page Title>](<related-slug>.md) — <one-line reason for connection>\n- [<Another Related Page>](<slug>.md) — <connection reason>\n\n## Sources\n\n- <path/to/source/file or URL where this came from>\n- Ingested: <YYYY-MM-DD>\n```\n\n---\n\n## Good Example\n\n```markdown\n# Retrieval Augmented Generation\n\nTechnique that grounds LLM responses in retrieved documents rather than\nrelying solely on training data.\n\n## Key Points\n\n- Combines a retriever (vector search) with a generator (LLM)\n- Reduces hallucination by providing source documents as context\n- Trade-off: retrieval quality limits generation quality\n- Common stack: embeddings → vector DB → reranker → LLM prompt\n- Works best when source corpus is well-chunked and up-to-date\n\n## Related\n\n- [Vector Databases](vector-databases.md) — the retrieval layer in RAG pipelines\n- [Agent Eval Harness](agent-eval-harness.md) — uses embedding similarity for judge calibration\n\n## Sources\n\n- ~/second-brain/sources/what-is-rag.md\n- Ingested: 2026-06-10\n```\n\n---\n\n## Bad Example\n\n```markdown\n# RAG\n\nRetrieval Augmented Generation (RAG) is a technique in artificial intelligence\nthat combines information retrieval with text generation. It was first proposed\nby Lewis et al. in 2020. The basic idea is that instead of relying solely on\nwhat a language model learned during training, you can augment it with relevant\ndocuments retrieved at inference time.\n\nThis approach has several advantages. First, it reduces hallucination because\nthe model can reference actual documents. Second, it allows the model to access\nup-to-date information that wasn't in its training data. Third, it provides\ntransparency because you can trace responses back to source documents.\n\nThere are several implementations of RAG available today...\n```\n\n**Why it's bad:**\n- Reads like a Wikipedia article, not a wiki node\n- No bullet summaries (walls of prose)\n- No Related section (isolated page, no connections)\n- No Sources section (where did this come from?)\n- Title is an acronym without expansion\n- Contains filler (\"There are several...\" \"This approach has...\")\n","numLines":90,"startLine":1,"totalLines":90}}}
