{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_01U9sXsENTrdNtRZZCPvQ16t","type":"tool_result","content":"agent-eval-harness.md\nai-first-sync-2026-06-25.md\nai-sdlc-pipeline.md\nandy-evan-2026-06-22.md\nandy-evan-2026-06-29.md\nandy-evan-eval-review-2026-06-16.md\nansible-ai-helpers-strategy-2026-06-17.md\ncursor-work-2026-06-16.md\ndecision-kit.md\nevaluator-super-agent.md\nindex.md\nlog.md\nmidpoint-checkin-2026-06-30.md\nmy-cursor-claw.md\nnielsens-heuristics-jagged-edge.md\noutcome-tiger-team.md\nprompt-engineering-best-practices.md\nprototype-creator-demo-may14.md\nprototype-creator.md\nredhat-ai-first-lessons.md\nretrieval-augmented-generation.md\nrfe-creator.md\nrh-ai-first-ux-2026-06-18.md\nrh-ai-first-ux-2026-06-25.md\nsession-log-2026-06-15.md\nsession-log-2026-06-16.md\nskill-overlays.md\nstandup-2026-06-22.md\nstandup-2026-06-29.md\nux-quality-rubric.md\nvector-databases.md\nvector-similarity-search.md\nweekly-design-sync-2026-07-01.md\nwg-uxd-efficiency-2026-06-29.md\nzack-evan-2026-06-24.md\n---SEPARATOR---\n==> /Users/ejaquez/second-brain/wiki/agent-eval-harness.md <==\n# Agent Eval Harness\n\nA framework for evaluating AI agent skill quality through automated testing, judge scoring, and iterative optimization.\n\n## How It Works\n\n1. **eval.yaml** — defines execution mode, dataset schema, output descriptions, judges, models, and thresholds\n2. **Dataset** — test cases with realistic inputs for the skill\n3. **Judges** — automated scorers that rate skill outputs against criteria\n4. **Run** — executes the skill against test cases, scores with judges, reports results\n\n==> /Users/ejaquez/second-brain/wiki/ai-first-sync-2026-06-25.md <==\n# AI-First Sync -- June 25, 2026\n\nRed Hat AI UXD AI-First Sync. Evan's prototype evaluator presentation and 3.6 branch strategy.\n\n## Key Discussion Points\n\n- **3.6 branch available:** N10 URL auto-updates. Aim to adopt real codebase by mid 3.6/3.7 cycle. PRs still target 3.5, easily migratable.\n- **Prototype evaluator demo:** Evan presented the evaluator architecture to the full team. Extracts Jira data (RFEs, MRs, acceptance criteria), classifies into evaluation tiers, inspects MR deltas for missing UI elements and accessibility gaps.\n- **Playwright integration:** Automated usability testing via user journeys generated from acceptance criteria. System verifies presence of necessary controls. MR data provides \"colleague hints\" to personas (affects scores).\n- **Iteration and flagging:** System attempts auto-fixes for flagged issues; subjective items set aside for human review. Designers/PMs can override flags.\n\n==> /Users/ejaquez/second-brain/wiki/ai-sdlc-pipeline.md <==\n# AI-SDLC Pipeline\n\nRed Hat's AI-assisted Software Development Life Cycle — a three-phase pipeline where each phase has its own \"creator\" tool.\n\n## The Three Phases\n\n| Phase | Project | Role | Repo |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Phase 1: The WHAT | [RFE Creator](rfe-creator.md) | Creates and assesses RFEs in Jira | opendatahub-io/rfe-creator |\n| Phase 2: The SHOW | [Prototype Creator](prototype-creator.md) | Makes the experience tangible through clickable prototypes | andybraren/prototype-creator |\n\n==> /Users/ejaquez/second-brain/wiki/andy-evan-2026-06-22.md <==\n# Andy/Evan Meeting -- June 22, 2026\n\n1:1 review of evaluation system progress and prototype creator integration strategy.\n\n## Key Discussion Points\n\n- **Evaluation harness progress:** Iteration history now tracks original and final reports with summaries of fixes. Usability scores improved from 11 to 19 after agent corrected blank table values.\n- **Flagging system:** Complex failures flagged for human review (console errors, browser permissions). Fixable items auto-corrected after multiple flagged iterations.\n- **Prototype Creator integration:** Andy suggested spinning up a sub-agent running Prototype Creator when acceptance criteria fails. Evan raised cost concerns, proposing invoking the skill only for complex issues while handling minor fixes internally.\n- **Style guidelines:** Consistency checker not yet merged into Prototype Creator, but planned for maintaining Red Hat style standards during automated evaluations.\n\n==> /Users/ejaquez/second-brain/wiki/andy-evan-2026-06-29.md <==\n# Andy/Evan Meeting -- June 29, 2026\n\n1:1 covering prototype evaluator progress, reporting infrastructure, repository strategy, and future directions.\n\n## Key Discussion Points\n\n- **Persona walkthroughs separated:** Fixed overlap issue. Developing \"Findings\" tab documenting issues and resolutions. Implementing \"Auto-fix\" vs \"Report-only\" modes to manage regressions.\n- **Data discrepancies:** Patient scores fluctuating without clear explanation. Investigating inconsistencies.\n- **Jira entity confusion:** Clarified RF (Product Managers create) → Strat relationship. Prototype Creator should ideally link to RF (upstream). \"UI Direction\" section in Strat documents remains useful for prototyping.\n- **Token optimization:** Configure AI to extract only necessary sections (e.g., \"UI Direction\") rather than ingesting entire Strat documents. Need to confirm if it's a hardcoded heading.\n\n==> /Users/ejaquez/second-brain/wiki/andy-evan-eval-review-2026-06-16.md <==\n# Andy/Evan Evaluation Review — June 16, 2026\n\nMeeting with Andy Braren reviewing the prototype evaluation system. Three key decisions shaped the direction of the evaluator super agent.\n\n## Key Decisions\n\n- **Outcomes over Strategic Goals** — The evaluation framework will use Jira Outcomes as primary grounding criteria, not Strategic Goals. Outcomes contain reliable user journey definitions; Strats are inconsistently written and would confuse the agent.\n- **Super evaluator architecture** — Consolidate fragmented individual skills (usability, consistency, desirability) into a single centralized evaluation agent. One Playwright pass, shared screenshots, reduced token usage.\n- **Overlay architecture** — 98% generic evaluator + 2% product-specific overlay. Follows the pattern from Global Engineering's [wg-agentic-sdlc skill-overlays best practice](https://gitlab.cee.redhat.com/global-engineering/wg-agentic-sdlc/-/blob/main/best-practices/skill-overlays.md).\n\n\n==> /Users/ejaquez/second-brain/wiki/ansible-ai-helpers-strategy-2026-06-17.md <==\n# Ansible AI Helpers Strategy — 2026-06-17\n\nStrategy session on integrating the UXD AI Helpers repo with Ansible's Carbonite harness. First major external consumer of the centralized skill distribution model.\n\n## Attendees\n\nJeremy Perry, Mike Franke, Nicole Thoen, Jeff Puzzo, Cate Ferman, Leslie Hinson, Andy Braren, Melissa Grimes (invited: Taufique Rahman)\n\n## Context\n\n\n==> /Users/ejaquez/second-brain/wiki/cursor-work-2026-06-16.md <==\n# Cursor Agent Work — June 16, 2026\n\nA daily record of all agent work done across 4 Cursor sessions on this date. Focused on productivity infrastructure: skills that make other skills better, zero-friction workflows, and manager-oriented accountability.\n\n## Sessions\n\n### 1. Trend-Scan Research Skill\nCreated `~/.cursor/skills/trend-scan/` — scans Reddit, HN, Twitter/X, Stack Overflow for trends and sentiment. Outputs an interactive Canvas. Use cases: researching before building skills, evaluating agent frameworks, investment research.\n\n### 2. Batch Skill Creation\n\n==> /Users/ejaquez/second-brain/wiki/decision-kit.md <==\n# Decision Kit\n\nA toolkit for Decision Driven Development. AI does the busywork around your decisions — you make the calls.\n\n## Core Concept\n\nYou bring a situation. Decision Kit surfaces 5–7 decisions hiding inside it, stack-ranked from most critical to least. For each one, it gathers research, builds options, renders visual previews, lays out tradeoffs as side-by-side comparisons. Then it stops and waits for you to decide. Every decision becomes a browsable HTML artifact in `.decisions/`.\n\n## Two Types of Skills\n\n\n==> /Users/ejaquez/second-brain/wiki/evaluator-super-agent.md <==\n# Evaluator Super Agent\n\nEvan's primary assignment: build an evaluation agent that automates prototype quality assessment within the [Prototype Creator](prototype-creator.md) pipeline.\n\n**Status: Shipped.** The evaluator is a 3-phase skill pipeline on branch `evan/prototype-evaluate` at [andybraren/prototype-creator](https://github.com/andybraren/prototype-creator). It has evaluated 18+ STRATs against Jira acceptance criteria with Playwright persona walkthroughs.\n\n## What It Does (current)\n\n| Capability | Source | Status |\n|---|---|---|\n\n==> /Users/ejaquez/second-brain/wiki/index.md <==\n# Wiki Index\n\nA catalog of all wiki pages, organized by category.\n\n## Red Hat AI-SDLC\n\n- [Red Hat AI-First Lessons](redhat-ai-first-lessons.md) — Jeremy Eder's presentation on agentic SDLC, issue-to-PR bots, eval infrastructure, AgentReady, and culture shifts\n- [Outcome Tiger Team](outcome-tiger-team.md) — proposal to formalize outcomes as the upstream step feeding the entire pipeline\n- [AI-SDLC Pipeline](ai-sdlc-pipeline.md) — the three-phase pipeline (WHAT → SHOW → HOW)\n- [RFE Creator](rfe-creator.md) — Phase 1: creates and assesses RFEs in Jira\n\n==> /Users/ejaquez/second-brain/wiki/log.md <==\n# Change Log\n\nA chronological record of all wiki operations.\n\n## 2026-07-09 — Duplicate detected: Vector Similarity Search\n- No new page created — content already fully covered by vector-similarity-search.md\n- All 4 key points in the new source were already present in the existing page (with more detail)\n- No updates needed; existing page is current and complete\n\n## 2026-07-09 — Ingested: Prompt Engineering Best Practices\n\n==> /Users/ejaquez/second-brain/wiki/midpoint-checkin-2026-06-30.md <==\n# Midpoint Check-in with Zack -- June 30, 2026\n\nHalfway internship check-in focused on growth, energy management, strengths/opportunities feedback, and career direction. Not a work-progress meeting.\n\n## Zack's Feedback: Strengths\n\n- Evan's background is \"very unique and very well suited\" for this kind of AI + research + design work. Zack had to rewrite the entire job description: \"we don't need a research intern. We need an intern who can come in and help us figure out what the next model of working with AI looks like for research.\"\n- The prototype evaluator work is \"pioneering work\" that encapsulates research into an AI framework inside the ADLC. These three things (research, AI skill, SDLC integration) rarely come together in one actual capability.\n- Evan handles ambiguous/murky situations well. \"Not being afraid to generate clarity is a really really important skill.\" Most people assume they should already know the answer, but often nobody knows.\n- Engagement with stakeholders is strong. Zack described it as \"collaborative curiosity\" which resonates with Red Hat culture.\n\n==> /Users/ejaquez/second-brain/wiki/my-cursor-claw.md <==\n# My Cursor Claw\n\nPersonal skill development workspace built during the Day of Learning Agent Skills Workshop (2026-06-05). Contains 20+ custom Cursor skills, 5 MCP server connections, and automated daily review infrastructure.\n\n## MCP Connections\n\n- **Atlassian** — Jira issues, JQL search, transitions, Confluence\n- **Dataverse** — SQL queries against Red Hat data products\n- **PatternFly Docs** — component documentation and design tokens\n- **Google Workspace (gws)** — Docs, Slides, Drive, Calendar, Gmail\n\n==> /Users/ejaquez/second-brain/wiki/nielsens-heuristics-jagged-edge.md <==\n# Nielsen's Heuristics & The Jagged Edge\n\nFirst hands-on internship assignment: apply Nielsen Norman's 10 Usability Heuristics to Kubernetes-style interfaces across multiple AI tools and compare their analysis quality.\n\n## The Jagged Edge\n\nResearch from Harvard Business School shows AI capabilities aren't uniform — models are very good at some tasks and surprisingly bad at others. The boundary between \"good\" and \"bad\" isn't obvious. This is the \"jagged technological frontier.\"\n\n## What Was Tested\n\n\n==> /Users/ejaquez/second-brain/wiki/outcome-tiger-team.md <==\n# Outcome Tiger Team\n\nProposal by Andy Braren to form a cross-functional tiger team focused on the critical step *before* the [AI-SDLC Pipeline](ai-sdlc-pipeline.md): creating, prioritizing, and visualizing **outcomes** — the directional goals that determine which features get prioritized and why.\n\nRepo: [andybraren/outcome-creator](https://github.com/andybraren/outcome-creator)\nMiro: [Concept board](https://miro.com/app/board/uXjVHacm2cA=/)\n\n## The Problem\n\nToday many RFEs and STRATs are never connected to higher-level outcomes. When they are, priorities come from informal synthesis across scattered sources (customer escalations, SA calls, analyst reports, UX research, POCs, partner input, upstream signals). The rationale behind outcomes is rarely captured in a reusable way. An Agentic SDLC amplifies these gaps — automating feature delivery without clear outcomes just ships a \"myopic grab bag\" faster.\n\n==> /Users/ejaquez/second-brain/wiki/prompt-engineering-best-practices.md <==\n# Prompt Engineering Best Practices\n\nCore techniques for writing effective LLM prompts that produce consistent, high-quality outputs.\n\n## Key Points\n\n- **Specify output format explicitly** — tell the model what structure you expect (JSON, bullets, table, prose) rather than inferring it","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"26577a53-3272-4cd4-9d88-de04f8cb372b","uuid":"b59f7e57-d2a5-4623-823e-f1144883a5a8","timestamp":"2026-07-09T15:57:54.046Z","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"agent-eval-harness.md\nai-first-sync-2026-06-25.md\nai-sdlc-pipeline.md\nandy-evan-2026-06-22.md\nandy-evan-2026-06-29.md\nandy-evan-eval-review-2026-06-16.md\nansible-ai-helpers-strategy-2026-06-17.md\ncursor-work-2026-06-16.md\ndecision-kit.md\nevaluator-super-agent.md\nindex.md\nlog.md\nmidpoint-checkin-2026-06-30.md\nmy-cursor-claw.md\nnielsens-heuristics-jagged-edge.md\noutcome-tiger-team.md\nprompt-engineering-best-practices.md\nprototype-creator-demo-may14.md\nprototype-creator.md\nredhat-ai-first-lessons.md\nretrieval-augmented-generation.md\nrfe-creator.md\nrh-ai-first-ux-2026-06-18.md\nrh-ai-first-ux-2026-06-25.md\nsession-log-2026-06-15.md\nsession-log-2026-06-16.md\nskill-overlays.md\nstandup-2026-06-22.md\nstandup-2026-06-29.md\nux-quality-rubric.md\nvector-databases.md\nvector-similarity-search.md\nweekly-design-sync-2026-07-01.md\nwg-uxd-efficiency-2026-06-29.md\nzack-evan-2026-06-24.md\n---SEPARATOR---\n==> /Users/ejaquez/second-brain/wiki/agent-eval-harness.md <==\n# Agent Eval Harness\n\nA framework for evaluating AI agent skill quality through automated testing, judge scoring, and iterative optimization.\n\n## How It Works\n\n1. **eval.yaml** — defines execution mode, dataset schema, output descriptions, judges, models, and thresholds\n2. **Dataset** — test cases with realistic inputs for the skill\n3. **Judges** — automated scorers that rate skill outputs against criteria\n4. **Run** — executes the skill against test cases, scores with judges, reports results\n\n==> /Users/ejaquez/second-brain/wiki/ai-first-sync-2026-06-25.md <==\n# AI-First Sync -- June 25, 2026\n\nRed Hat AI UXD AI-First Sync. Evan's prototype evaluator presentation and 3.6 branch strategy.\n\n## Key Discussion Points\n\n- **3.6 branch available:** N10 URL auto-updates. Aim to adopt real codebase by mid 3.6/3.7 cycle. PRs still target 3.5, easily migratable.\n- **Prototype evaluator demo:** Evan presented the evaluator architecture to the full team. Extracts Jira data (RFEs, MRs, acceptance criteria), classifies into evaluation tiers, inspects MR deltas for missing UI elements and accessibility gaps.\n- **Playwright integration:** Automated usability testing via user journeys generated from acceptance criteria. System verifies presence of necessary controls. MR data provides \"colleague hints\" to personas (affects scores).\n- **Iteration and flagging:** System attempts auto-fixes for flagged issues; subjective items set aside for human review. Designers/PMs can override flags.\n\n==> /Users/ejaquez/second-brain/wiki/ai-sdlc-pipeline.md <==\n# AI-SDLC Pipeline\n\nRed Hat's AI-assisted Software Development Life Cycle — a three-phase pipeline where each phase has its own \"creator\" tool.\n\n## The Three Phases\n\n| Phase | Project | Role | Repo |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Phase 1: The WHAT | [RFE Creator](rfe-creator.md) | Creates and assesses RFEs in Jira | opendatahub-io/rfe-creator |\n| Phase 2: The SHOW | [Prototype Creator](prototype-creator.md) | Makes the experience tangible through clickable prototypes | andybraren/prototype-creator |\n\n==> /Users/ejaquez/second-brain/wiki/andy-evan-2026-06-22.md <==\n# Andy/Evan Meeting -- June 22, 2026\n\n1:1 review of evaluation system progress and prototype creator integration strategy.\n\n## Key Discussion Points\n\n- **Evaluation harness progress:** Iteration history now tracks original and final reports with summaries of fixes. Usability scores improved from 11 to 19 after agent corrected blank table values.\n- **Flagging system:** Complex failures flagged for human review (console errors, browser permissions). Fixable items auto-corrected after multiple flagged iterations.\n- **Prototype Creator integration:** Andy suggested spinning up a sub-agent running Prototype Creator when acceptance criteria fails. Evan raised cost concerns, proposing invoking the skill only for complex issues while handling minor fixes internally.\n- **Style guidelines:** Consistency checker not yet merged into Prototype Creator, but planned for maintaining Red Hat style standards during automated evaluations.\n\n==> /Users/ejaquez/second-brain/wiki/andy-evan-2026-06-29.md <==\n# Andy/Evan Meeting -- June 29, 2026\n\n1:1 covering prototype evaluator progress, reporting infrastructure, repository strategy, and future directions.\n\n## Key Discussion Points\n\n- **Persona walkthroughs separated:** Fixed overlap issue. Developing \"Findings\" tab documenting issues and resolutions. Implementing \"Auto-fix\" vs \"Report-only\" modes to manage regressions.\n- **Data discrepancies:** Patient scores fluctuating without clear explanation. Investigating inconsistencies.\n- **Jira entity confusion:** Clarified RF (Product Managers create) → Strat relationship. Prototype Creator should ideally link to RF (upstream). \"UI Direction\" section in Strat documents remains useful for prototyping.\n- **Token optimization:** Configure AI to extract only necessary sections (e.g., \"UI Direction\") rather than ingesting entire Strat documents. Need to confirm if it's a hardcoded heading.\n\n==> /Users/ejaquez/second-brain/wiki/andy-evan-eval-review-2026-06-16.md <==\n# Andy/Evan Evaluation Review — June 16, 2026\n\nMeeting with Andy Braren reviewing the prototype evaluation system. Three key decisions shaped the direction of the evaluator super agent.\n\n## Key Decisions\n\n- **Outcomes over Strategic Goals** — The evaluation framework will use Jira Outcomes as primary grounding criteria, not Strategic Goals. Outcomes contain reliable user journey definitions; Strats are inconsistently written and would confuse the agent.\n- **Super evaluator architecture** — Consolidate fragmented individual skills (usability, consistency, desirability) into a single centralized evaluation agent. One Playwright pass, shared screenshots, reduced token usage.\n- **Overlay architecture** — 98% generic evaluator + 2% product-specific overlay. Follows the pattern from Global Engineering's [wg-agentic-sdlc skill-overlays best practice](https://gitlab.cee.redhat.com/global-engineering/wg-agentic-sdlc/-/blob/main/best-practices/skill-overlays.md).\n\n\n==> /Users/ejaquez/second-brain/wiki/ansible-ai-helpers-strategy-2026-06-17.md <==\n# Ansible AI Helpers Strategy — 2026-06-17\n\nStrategy session on integrating the UXD AI Helpers repo with Ansible's Carbonite harness. First major external consumer of the centralized skill distribution model.\n\n## Attendees\n\nJeremy Perry, Mike Franke, Nicole Thoen, Jeff Puzzo, Cate Ferman, Leslie Hinson, Andy Braren, Melissa Grimes (invited: Taufique Rahman)\n\n## Context\n\n\n==> /Users/ejaquez/second-brain/wiki/cursor-work-2026-06-16.md <==\n# Cursor Agent Work — June 16, 2026\n\nA daily record of all agent work done across 4 Cursor sessions on this date. Focused on productivity infrastructure: skills that make other skills better, zero-friction workflows, and manager-oriented accountability.\n\n## Sessions\n\n### 1. Trend-Scan Research Skill\nCreated `~/.cursor/skills/trend-scan/` — scans Reddit, HN, Twitter/X, Stack Overflow for trends and sentiment. Outputs an interactive Canvas. Use cases: researching before building skills, evaluating agent frameworks, investment research.\n\n### 2. Batch Skill Creation\n\n==> /Users/ejaquez/second-brain/wiki/decision-kit.md <==\n# Decision Kit\n\nA toolkit for Decision Driven Development. AI does the busywork around your decisions — you make the calls.\n\n## Core Concept\n\nYou bring a situation. Decision Kit surfaces 5–7 decisions hiding inside it, stack-ranked from most critical to least. For each one, it gathers research, builds options, renders visual previews, lays out tradeoffs as side-by-side comparisons. Then it stops and waits for you to decide. Every decision becomes a browsable HTML artifact in `.decisions/`.\n\n## Two Types of Skills\n\n\n==> /Users/ejaquez/second-brain/wiki/evaluator-super-agent.md <==\n# Evaluator Super Agent\n\nEvan's primary assignment: build an evaluation agent that automates prototype quality assessment within the [Prototype Creator](prototype-creator.md) pipeline.\n\n**Status: Shipped.** The evaluator is a 3-phase skill pipeline on branch `evan/prototype-evaluate` at [andybraren/prototype-creator](https://github.com/andybraren/prototype-creator). It has evaluated 18+ STRATs against Jira acceptance criteria with Playwri