{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_01EfVtarbnd99CML5PuPyrdB","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Prompt Engineering Best Practices\n2\t\n3\tCore techniques for writing effective LLM prompts that produce consistent, high-quality outputs.\n4\t\n5\t## Key Points\n6\t\n7\t- **Specify output format explicitly** — tell the model what structure you expect (JSON, bullets, table, prose) rather than inferring it\n8\t- **Provide examples of good and bad output** — few-shot examples anchor the model more reliably than descriptions alone\n9\t- **Use chain-of-thought for complex reasoning** — instruct the model to reason step-by-step before answering; improves accuracy on multi-hop problems\n10\t- **Break multi-step tasks into sequential prompts** — a pipeline of focused prompts outperforms one sprawling mega-prompt\n11\t- **Include constraints and boundaries explicitly** — state what the model should NOT do as clearly as what it should\n12\t\n13\t## Related\n14\t\n15\t- [Agent Eval Harness](agent-eval-harness.md) — judge prompts are the core of the eval harness; format specs and CoT directly improve scoring accuracy\n16\t- [Skill Overlays](skill-overlays.md) — overlays are structured prompts with explicit constraints and project-specific examples baked in\n17\t- [Evaluator Super Agent](evaluator-super-agent.md) — each evaluation phase uses format-controlled output and sequential prompting across phases\n18\t\n19\t## Sources\n20\t\n21\t- ~/second-brain/sources/2026-06-15-prompt-engineering-best-practices.md\n22\t- Ingested: 2026-07-09\n23\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"26577a53-3272-4cd4-9d88-de04f8cb372b","uuid":"18f99c79-2a9e-4c43-b6db-88e0b0a63f02","timestamp":"2026-07-09T15:57:56.741Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/ejaquez/second-brain/wiki/prompt-engineering-best-practices.md","content":"# Prompt Engineering Best Practices\n\nCore techniques for writing effective LLM prompts that produce consistent, high-quality outputs.\n\n## Key Points\n\n- **Specify output format explicitly** — tell the model what structure you expect (JSON, bullets, table, prose) rather than inferring it\n- **Provide examples of good and bad output** — few-shot examples anchor the model more reliably than descriptions alone\n- **Use chain-of-thought for complex reasoning** — instruct the model to reason step-by-step before answering; improves accuracy on multi-hop problems\n- **Break multi-step tasks into sequential prompts** — a pipeline of focused prompts outperforms one sprawling mega-prompt\n- **Include constraints and boundaries explicitly** — state what the model should NOT do as clearly as what it should\n\n## Related\n\n- [Agent Eval Harness](agent-eval-harness.md) — judge prompts are the core of the eval harness; format specs and CoT directly improve scoring accuracy\n- [Skill Overlays](skill-overlays.md) — overlays are structured prompts with explicit constraints and project-specific examples baked in\n- [Evaluator Super Agent](evaluator-super-agent.md) — each evaluation phase uses format-controlled output and sequential prompting across phases\n\n## Sources\n\n- ~/second-brain/sources/2026-06-15-prompt-engineering-best-practices.md\n- Ingested: 2026-07-09\n","numLines":23,"startLine":1,"totalLines":23}}}
